column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING GASOLINE INTO CUSTOMER'S TANK.  THERE IS A "T" CONNECTION ON THE PUMP SO IT CAN BE UNLOADED FROM EITHER SIDE.  THE CAP ON THE OTHER SIDE FROM WHERE THE DRIVER WAS HOOKED CAME LOOSE AND BLEW OFF.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP NUT SPILLED APPROX. 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  AFTER SECURING THE CAP HE GOT A SHOVEL AND DIKED UP THE GAS SO IT COULDN'T GO INTO DRAIN.  HE THEN CALLED THE FIRE DEPT.  AND DISPATCH.  THE SAND WAS THEN PICKED UP AND TAKEN TO OUR TERMINAL WHERE IT IS BEING AERATED.  DRIVERS ARE SUPPOSED TO TIE DOWN ALL CAMLOCK FITTINGS BUT FAILED TO IN THIS INCIDENT.

PARCEL WAS LEAKING WHEN UNLOADED FROM TRAILER DUE TO IMPROPER INNER PACK. DAMAGED PORTION WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE ITEMS INSIDE OF THE CARTON, THEY WERE FOUND BE D.O.T. REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERAILS.  THERE WERE THREE (3) PAILS INSIDE PACKAGE.  TWO (2) WERE NA 1133 AND ONE (1) WAS LABELLED: LIQUID CLEANER. THERE WERE NO DIAMOND LABELS OR 5-PART FORMS TO IDENTIFY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE PAILS WERE PACKED ON THEIR SIDE AND THE ONLY INNER PACKING WAS SCHREDDED PAPER.  THE CANS HAD NO CAN LID CLIPS.  THE OUTSIDE CARTON HAD NO SHIPPER THIS APPEARS TO BE A CONCEALED SHIPMENT SINCE THIS PACKAGE HAD NO OUTSIDE MARKING OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LABELS. CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD VISIT THIS SHIPPER AND EXPLAIN PROPER PROCEDURE FOR SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

CSXT HAZMAT RECEIVED A REPORT OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT CALHOUN, GA.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AND CALLED CSX.  THE TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE LOCALLY AND THEY INSPECTED THE CAR. CAR LEAKED WHILE SITTING STILL.  CAR WAS OVERLOADED.  CAR WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE SO THAT IT COULD BE UNLOADED IMMEDIATELY.

ON THE TRAILER WHEN DRIVER RETURNED TO SERVICE CENTER.  THE EXCESSIVE TRAVEL TO FROM THE CUSTOMER WITH NO BLOCKING WAS TOO MUCH STRESS FOR THE SHRINK WRAP.  THE FRT WAS APPARENTLY STACKED 3 HIGH.  THE TOP LAYERS BROKE THROUGH THE SHRINK WRAP, CONTAINERS FELL TO THE FLOOR OF TRL, 11 BROKE OPEN & SPILLED CONTENTS. TRL WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE DOCK WHEN DISCOVERED, LOCKED AND ISOLATED FROM TRAFFIC.  SAFETY DEPT.  FIRE DEPT & 911 WERE NOTIFIED.  FIRE DEPT CONDUCTED CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.  DRIVER MEETINGS WERE HELD THIS AM TO DISCUSS HANDLING, BLOCKING AND STACKING OF HM SHIPMENTS.  FRT SHOULD NOT TRAVEL 3 HIGH.

column168: LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS FOUND WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER.  AT THE TIME OF UNLOADING IT WAS NOT IDENTIFIABLE AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  AFTER IT WAS UNLOADED THE PAPERWORK WAS CHECKED AND THE CRUSHED CARTON WAS THEN IDENTIFIED AS BEING HAZARDOUS.  AT THAT POINT THE AREA AROUND THE CONTAMINATED BOX WAS SECURED, THE SHIPPER AND A SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE WERE CALLED, AND EMPLOYEES THAT HANDLED THE FREIGHT WERE BROUHGT INTO THE OFFICE AND LATER SENT FOR OBSERVATION.  TO PREVENT CONTAMINATION OF EMPLOYEES IN THE FUTURE, EMPLOYEES WILL CHECK PAPERWORK BEFORE HANDLING DAMAGED/LEAKING FREIGHT.

column168: CREW REPORTED THAT THEY SMELLED A STRONG ODOR ABOUT TEN CARS FROM WEST END AS THEY CAME THROUGH 007 TRACK.  AT WEST END TANK CARS WERE IN 003 TRACK, I LOCATED CAR CELX 23236 THAT WAS VENTING FROM TOP AROUNG MANWAY COVER.  I TIGHTENED MANWAY COVER BOLTS BUT COULD NOT STOP THE ODOR.  I OPENED MANWAY COVER AND FOUND THAT GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE ON LEFT SIDE.  I STRAIGHTENED GASKET AND RECLOSED MANWAY COVER.  NO CREWS WERE ALLOWED TO MOVE IN THIS AREA AFTER IT WAS REPORTED UNTIL REPAIRS WERE MADE. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY MINUTES.

column168: 20 PAILS OF SULFURIC ACID-CORROSIVE MATERIAL UN1830 CAME INTO YORK ON TRAILER 37368 WITH ONE PAIL LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THERE WAS A SMALL PINHOLE AND THE LEAKAGE WAS MINIMAL.  WE CALLED JONES CHEMICAL AND TALKED TO DAVE MEAK WHO INSTRUCTED US TO STOP THE LEAK IF WE COULD AND SEND IT BACK TO HIM.  WE PATCHED THE PAIL WITH ALUMINIUM TRAILER TAPE AND WRAPPED THE PAIL IN PLASTIC GBAGS AND SHIPPED UPSIDE DOWN BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  WE SENT THE 19 OTHER PAILS AHEAD TO DESTINATION AND DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

CSW DRIVER HAD LEFT SHERMAN, TX. FOR A PICKUP IN ATOKA, OK.  WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR HE DISCOVERED THE LEAKAGE.  UPON CHECKING THE LEAKAGE FURTHER, HE FOUND THAT (1) OF THE PAILS HAD FALLEN OFF A SHRINKWRAPPED PALLET, AND UPON STRIKING THE FLOOR, THE LID WAS SEPARATED FROM THE PAIL.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE SAFETY DEPT, DESCRIBING THE INCIDENT AND THE MATERIAL INVOLVED, AND AT THAT TIME EM-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  UPON EM-TECH ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, ALL CONTAMINATED FREIGHT WAS DE-CONTAMINATED ALONG WITH ALL LEAKING MATERIAL BEING NEUTRALIZED.  PAILS WILL BE STACKED ON THE FLOOR, NO MORE THAT (2) HIGH, TO ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF THIS REOCCURING.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT OF 42 CARDBOARD CARTONS OF PRECURED TREAD STOCK RUBBER ABD 2 LOOSE PAILS OF ADHESIVE LIQUID.  THIS WAS LOADED ON 2 SHRINK WRAPPED SKDS WITH THE 2 PAILS ON TOP OF ONE OF THE SKDS.  AS THE DRIVER WAS LOADING THE SKD WITH THE PAILS ON TOP HE INADVERTENTLY RAISED THE SKID TOO HIGH AND HIT THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WITH ONE OF THE PAILS.  THE PAIL WAS PARTIALLY CRUSHED AGAINST THE TOP OF THE TRAILER AND ABOUT A GALLON OF THE ADHESIVE WAS SPILLED.  THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS ABSORBED BY USING SAND AND CARDBOARD.  THE EXCESS LIQUID DRYED IN OPEN AIR AFTER ONLY A FEW MINUTES.  IN DISCUSSIONS WITH THE MANAGER OF CHEMICAL MATERIAL SAFETY WE LEARNED THE LIQUID WAS HAZARDOUS ONLY AS A LIQUID AND ONCE IT DRYED IT WAS NO LONGER FLAMMABLE.

column168: ON AUGUST 6, 1991, A NORTHER N ENERGY, INC., FLATBED TRUCK WAS TRANSPORTING TWO (2) 500 GALLON PROPANE TANKS.  AS THE TRUCK EXITED I-5 AND WAS TURNING LEFT ON 128TH STREET SOUTH EAST, A STRAP THAT WAS HOLDING THE PROPANE TANKS CAME LOOSE AND ONE 500 GALLON TANK ROLLED OFF OF THE TRUCK ONTO THE PAVEMENT, WHEN THE TANK HIT THE GROUND, THE SERVICE VALVE, FILL VALVE, AND CHECK LOCK VALVE WERE DAMAGED, CAUSING A PROPANE RELEASE. THE SITUATION WAS THEN BROUGHT UNDER CONTROL BY OUR EMPLOYEES AND THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR SECOND PARTY PROPERTY DAMAGE ASSOCIATED WITH THE INCIDENT. UPON RECEIVING NOTICE OF THIS OCCURRENCE, NORTHERN ENERGY HAS BEGUN REVIEW OF OUR TRAINING PROGRAM TO INSURE THAT THE PROPER PROCEDURES ARE EXECUTED IN THE SAFE HANDLING AND TRANSPORTATION OF LP GAS CONTAINERS, ALL MEASURES SHALL BE TAKEN TO PREVENT SUCH AN EVENT FROM RE-OCCURRING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS ON AUGUST 18, 1991, WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF RE-RAILING CELX 6424, TANK CAR, PLACARDED CORROSIVE-RESIDUE, APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF ACETIC ANHYDIRDE WAS RELEASED WHEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY BROKE OFF ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  EARLIER INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY DID NOT REVEAL A HAIR LINE CRACK THAT EXTENDED AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET PIPE ABOVE THE OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBY AND WHEN THE CAR MOVED THE OUTLET ASSEMBLY FELL OFF.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXMATELY 3 GALLONS OF ACETIC ANHYDRIDE WAS RELEASED INTO THE TRACK BALLAST. CHEMTECH NOTIFIED AT 4:20 P.M., AUGUST 18, 1991, AND ILLINOIS COMMERCE COMMISSION NOTIFIED AT 4:25 P.M., SAME DATE.  THE CHEMICAL DIVISION OF HULCHER EMERGENCY SERVICE WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 P.M., AUGUST 18, 1991, CONCERNING THE ABOVE AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PH LEVEL OF THE SOIL WAS CLOSE TO "4" AND AT THIS TIME A MIXTURE OF WATER AND BAKING SODA (15 LBS.)  WAS MIXED AND SPREAD OVER 2' X 2' AREA TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACETIC ANHYDRIDE THAT WAS ON THE GROUND.  AT A LATER DATE, NEW PH READINGS WILL BE MADE TO SEE WHETHER THE NEUTRALIZATION AGENT HAD A POSITIVE REACTION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, FRIDAY, AUGUST 2, 1991, A CONRAIL EMPLOYEE WORKING ALONG THE LEHIGH MAINLINE WEST OF MANVILLE, NJ OBSERVED TANK CAR NATX-29943 WITH LIQUID PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. CAR WAS LOCATED IN EASTBOUND CONRAIL TRAIN PIOI-2.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE CONRAIL DISPATCHERS OFFICE AND TRAIN CREW WAS ORDERED TO STOP THE TRAIN AT MANVILLE, NJ.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. UPON ARRIVAL TO THE MANVILLE RAIL YARD TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED BY CONRAIL TERMINAL GENERAL CAR FOREMAN B.G. HELTON WHO OBSERVED THAT ABOUT TEN DROPS PER MINUTE WERE DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA OF THE CAR.  A MORE DETAILED INSPECTION DISCOVERED THAT THE TOP OPERATING VALVE WAS OPEN APPROXIMATEY 1/2 TURN AND THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS ALSO LOOSE. ADDITIONALLY, THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR.  THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND PACKING GLAND WERE TIGHTENED ALONG THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP THEREBY SECURING THE LEAK.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 HOURS, AUGUST 2, 1991.

column168: OUR VAN WAS BEING UNLOADED.  2 DRUMS OF CAUSTIC SODA WERE LEFT IN PLACE ON THE VAN.  BY RELOADING THE VAN WITH CL2 CYLINDERS, THE METAL CYLINDER HOLDED EDGE CUT INTO ONE OF THE DRUMS AND CAUSED THE LEAK. THE CAUSTIC SODA LEAKED OUT OF THE TRUCK ONTO THE GROUND.  THE SPILL WAS AT ONCE CONTAINED WITH SODA ASH.  ALL THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED BY SODA ASH AND SHOVELED INTO DRUMS TO BE WORKED OFF IN OUR ELEMENTARY NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE, PLASTIC DRUMS HAVE TO BE OFF THE VAN TO ALLOW FREE PASSAGE FOR LIFT WITH CYLINDER BASKET.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS OUR VEHICLE OPERATOR CALLED ALERTING METROPOLITAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF A LEAKING PACKAGE.  HE WAS LOCATED IN BLOOMINGTON, ILLINOIS AT A UNOCAL TRUCKSTOP.  HE PULLED IN TO FUEL AND NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM HIS VEHICLE.  HE OPENED THE REAR DOORS AND NOTICED WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE ONE LEAKING PORTABLE TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY THE TRUCKSTOP.  HE PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CURTAIL ANY FURTHER SPREAD OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  AT THAT POINT HE NOTICED THAT THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A LOOSE CLOSURE ON THREE PORTABLE TANKS AND THAT THE SPILLING HAD STOPPED. HE CALLED OUR OFFICE THROUGH OR ANSWERING SERVICE AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO OUR IN-HOUSE SPILL COORDINATOR.  THE SPILL COORDINATOR IMPLEMENTED OUR WRITTEN SPILL CONTINGENCY PLAN.  SINCE THE FLOW HAD STOPPED AND THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND THERE WAS NO IMMINENT DANGER, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH OUT MAINTENANCE STAFF WHICH MOBILIZED EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL TO THE INCIDENT SITE.  THE ETA FOR THE CREW WAS APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS.  WHEN THE CREW ARRIVED THEY DONNED THE PROPER SAFETY EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  THEY RESEALED THE PORTABLE TANKS BY REPLACING THE GASKET MATERIAL AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED THE CLOSING MECHANISM.  ONCE SECURED, THEY USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO SOAK UP THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID THEN SHOVELED IT INTO AN OPEN TOP DRUM.  THE OPEN TOP DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO OUR UNCIE, INDIANA TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AT RCRA APPROVED FACILITY.  WORK COMPLETED AT APPROXMATELY 0500 HOURS.

column168: OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE TOP STAND PIPE AREA OF HIS CONTAINER TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE PA HIGHWAY PATROL, WHO THEN CALLED THE STATE HAZMAT TEAM.  AFTER THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT CLEANED UP AROUND THE STAND PIPE, THE STAND PIPE FLANGE WAS REMOVED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A GASKET WAS MISSING WHICH ALLOWED MATERIAL TO SLOSH FROM THE STAND PIPE AREA.  A NEW GASKET WAS INSERTED AND THE UNIT WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY ERIE ECOLOGICAL CONTRACTORS.  THEY PUT DOWN SODA ASH ON THE LIQUID PRODUCT AND THEN DISPOSED OF THE WASTE IN PROPER WASTE-DISPOSAL BARRELS. FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE CAN BE PREVENTED BY A MORE THOROUGH EXAMINATION OF THE TOP STAND PIPE - IN PARTICULAR, AN INSPECTION OF ALL GASKETS AND FLANGES.

THIS CAUSED 1 GALLON TO BE CRUSHED AND START LEAKING.  THE RESULT OF THE SPILL WAS 1 OTHER BOX WAS BOTTOM SOAKED BUT NO APPARENT DAMAGE. AFTER CALL TO SHIPPER IT AS DETERMINED THAT CLEANUP COULD EASILY BE MADE BY DOCKMAN.  THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL WAS SOAKED UP BY OIL SORB AND DISPOSED OF IN THE MANNER REPORTED BY SHIPPER.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN WASHED OUT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS SPILL.

WHILE MAKING A #2 FUEL OIL DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE CONSIGNEE'S 2,000 GALLON STORAGE TAK WAS OVERFILLED.  THIS CAUSED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE PRODUCT VENT AND LATER AT THE FILL LOCATION WHEN THE SHIPPER'S MOTOR VEHICLE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE HOSE.  ALL PRODUCT SPILLED (2 GALS.) WAS CONTAINED AND THE AREA CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT "SPEEDY DRY". HE STATED THAT BASED ON HIS BEFORE DELIVERY MEASUREMENT OF THE AFFECTED TANK, THE DELIVERY SHOULD HAVE BEEN ABLE TO BE COMPLETED SAFELY WITHOUT INCIDENT.  ACTUAL SIZE OF UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WILL BE DETERMINED TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER LEFT CWM/RR AND ARRIVED AT SWPC.  WHEN TURNING AROUND TO BACK UP PERSONNEL NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM OVERFLOW TUBE.  AT THAT TIME THE TANKER WAS PULLED IN CONTAINMENT AND THE DRIVER CALLED IN.  OHIO TRANS. & CWM/RR WERE NOTIFIED.  THE GENERAL MANAGER & DISPATCHER GOT IN THEIR CAR & WENT TO CWM/RR AND TRACED THE ROUTE THE TRUCK TOOK TO SWPC.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF MATERIAL UNTIL THEY REACHED SWPC.  CWM/RR ALSO RESPONDED BY TRACING THE ROUTE TAKEN BY THE TANKER.  THEY ALSO DISCOVERED NO LEAKAGE UNTIL THEY REACHED SWPC.  CWM.RR THEN CLEANED UP EVERYTHING ON THE TRAILER & PAVEMENT.  MEANWHILE, MAINTENANCE FROM OHIO TRANS. WENT OVER & REPLACED THE 1/4 INCH PLUG ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.  THE ENVIRONMENTALIST FROM SWPC MET WITH THE GENERAL MANAGER & DISPATCHER FROM OHIO TRANS. FAILED RUPTURE DISC WAS THEN REPLACED AND TANK PROCEEDED TO DESTINATION, WHERE IT WAS INSPECTED AND UNLOADED.  RELEASE OF MATERIAL WAS CAUSED BY HEAT BUILDUP IN TRAILER THUS CAUSING RUPTURE DISK TO FAIL.  A RUPTURE OF THIS TYPE IS VERY RARE IN FACT IN OUR 18 YEARS IN BUSINESS WE HAVE NEVER HAD AN INCIDENT OF THIS TYPE.  WE ARE CONSIDERING PUTTING A RELIEF VALVE IN LINE ABOVE THE RUPTURE DISK AS A SECONDARY BACK-UP.

column168: PRODUCT CAME OUT OF HOSE.  SECOND DEGREE BURNS TO DRIVER AND THIRD DEGREE BURNS TO HANDS DUE TO ACID GETTING INTO HIS GLOVES.

WHILE UNLOADING DENATURED ALCOHOL FROM OUR CARGO TANK INTO CENTRAL SOYA'S STORAGE TANK, THE 3" UNLOADING HOSE SPRUNG A LEAK.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT, BUT APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 GALLONS SEEPED FROM THE DEFECTIVE HOSE.  THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ONTO A GRAVEL LOT AND QUICKLY EVAPORATED IN THE EARLY MORNING SUN.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP EFFORTS NECESSARY. TO PREVENT FUTURE FAILURES OF THIS TYPE, ECOFF TRUCKING HAS IMPLEMENTED A THOROUGH BI-ANNUAL HOSE INSPECTION WHICH INCORPORATES A PRESSURE TEST AS WELL AS A LEAK TEST.  SUCH AN INSPECTION WILL ALLOW US TO BETTER MONITOR THE CONDITION OF THE HOSES AND REPLACE FAULTY HOSES PRIOR TO SUCH PRODUCT SPILLAGES AS THIS ONE.

column168: OUR TRANSPORT WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT.  THE COLLISION CAUSED THE RIGHT SIDE FUEL TANK (SADDLE TANK) ON OUR TRACTOR TO RUPTURE.  THE FUEL (DIESEL NO 2 ) LEAKING FROM THIS TANK IGNITED AND BURNED ON THE ROADWAY.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER STRUCK THE CONCRETE MEDIAN AND STOPPED. OBVIOUSLY THE ALUMINIUM TANK SUSTAINED A RUPTURE AS IT CONTACTED THE MEDIAN.  LEAKING GASOLINE WAS IGNITED BY THE BURNING DIESEL FUEL.  LOCAL FIRE OFFICIALS DECIDED TO ALLOW THE 8500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO BRUN TO PREVENT POSSIBLE ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AT EDGE OF ROADWAY AS A PRECAUTION. column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS: ON SUNDAY, AUGUST 11, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 P.M., THE ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES, INC. SHIFT FOREMAN PERFORMED A WALK-THROUGH INSPECTION OF THE ROSS TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. TRANSFER STATION. DURING THIS WALK-THROUGH THE FOREMAN OBSERVED A LEAKING TRAILER. ACTION TAKEN AT TIME DISCOVERED: THE FOREMAN CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE.  AN ABSORBENT DIKE WAS PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND ON THE GRAVEL DRIVE (WHERE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED). THE ROSS EMERGENCY COORDINATOR WAS CALLED TO THE FACILITY TO DIRECT RESPONSE ACTIONS. A PAPERWORK REVIEW TO DETERMINE THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WAS CONDUCTED. PERSONNEL DONNED APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THE ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES, INC. UNLOADING DOCK WHICH INCLUDES A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAD. ALL DRUMS WERE CARTED OFF THE TRAILER AND INSPECTED.  ONE LEAKING DRUM WAS DISCOVERED.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS SWEPT WITH FLOOR DRY. THE ROSS TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. TRANSFER STATION WAS REMEDIATED.  A BACKHOE WAS USED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  A TOTAL OF EIGHT (8) 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SPILL CLEAN UP (CONTAMINATED SOIL, ABSORBENT AND PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT) WAS GENERATED.  REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES WERE COMPLETED BY 6:30 P.M.  THE DRUMS WERE CHARACTERIZED AND THEN INCINERATED ON-SITE AT ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES, INC. AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS: THE RELEASE TO THE GRAVEL AREA OF THE TRANSFER STATION EXCEEDED THE 100 POUND REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR EPA WASTE CODE D003.  ROSS PROVIDED IMMEDIATE TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION TO BOTH THE U.S. EPA NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE OHIO EPA. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY ROSS TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, TO REVIEW THE INCIDENT AND TO DISCUSS PACKAGING.  A PROPER DOT CONTAINER WAS UTILIZED. ADDITIONAL SCRUTINY WILL BE IMPLEMENTED FOR FUTURE SHIPMENTS BY BOTH THE SHIPPER AND ROSS.

PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED DUE TO ODOR.  GLASS BOTTLE WAS BROKEN ON THE BOTTOM. THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL LEAKAGE DUE TO CONTAINMENT BY PLASTIC BAG AND PRESENCE OF ABSORBANT MATERIAL IN THE BOX.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR PACKCGAE DISPOSITION.

AFTER PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO ACCEPTING LOCATION, IT WAS INJECTED DUE TO INCOMPLETE DECLARATION: NO PARKING INSTRUCTION, NO PACKING GROUP, NO NAME AND TITLE, NO PLACE AND DATE.  THE PACKAGE WAS LATER ACCIDENTLY DROPPED ON THE FLOOR IN THE WAREHOUSE.  PACKAGED WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING OFFLOAD.  PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELLED OR OTHERWISE IDENTIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED.  MSDS INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS ACTUALLY A CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  PACKAGE WAS HELD AND FAA CONTACTED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0645 HOURS, THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER, 1991, EMPLOYEES WORKING AT AMERICAN RUBEBR COMPANY IN LAPORTE, INDIANA SMELLED PRODUCT ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAE TGPX-33604 (ANYHDROUS AMMONIA) LOCATE ON A SIDING TRACK BEHIND THE COMPANY.  COMPANY OFFICIALS NOTIIFED THE LA PORTE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED CONRAIL. CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE AND THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF THE VALVE AREA OF THE TANK CAR BY THE LA PORTE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM REVEALED THAT THE PRODUCT ODOR WAS COMING FROM A SMALL VALOR LEAK FROM ONE OF THE LIQUID LINE PLUGS.  AFTER DETERMING SAFE TO DO SO, THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO A ISOLATED AREA WEST OF LAPORTE.  DISTRICT INSPECTOR, T DAVIS OF THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1320 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 5, AND UPON INSPECTION DETERMINE THAT THAT THE THREE INCH "B" END LIQUID EDUCTION LINE VALVE WAS NOT SEATING PROPERLY AND THE PRODUCT VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM VALVE PLUG AND VALVE REDUCER LINE VALVE WAS NOT SEATING PROPERLY AND THE PRODUCT VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM VALVE PLUG AND VALVE REDUCER THREADS.  THE PLUG AND REDUCER WERE REMOVED FROM THE VALVE, CLEANED AND TAPED WITH TEFLON AT WHICH TIME THWY WERE RECONNECTED TO THE VALVE.  NO AUDIBLE LEAK OR PRODUCT VAPOR WERE DETECTED.  CAR CLEARED TO CONSIGNEE AT 1500 HOURS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, FRIDAY, AUGUST 30, 1991, EMPLOYEES ON CONRAIL TRAIN OIPI-9 SMELLED CHEMICAL ODOR COMING FROM TANK CARS RAIX-2708 AND RAIX-2715 IN THE TRAIN.  CARS WERE ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WERE NOTIFIED.  CRESSON, PA FIRE DEPT., ALSO RESPONDED.  AFTER THE CARS WERE EXAMINED BY THE CRESSON FIRE DEPARTMENT THEY SET OUT OF THE TRAIN TO TRACK #5 WEST AT THE CONRAIL CRESSON, PA RAIL YARD.  SENIOR INSPECTOR T. MANNAS OF THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CARS AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, AUGUST 30, AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS OF TANK CAR RAIX-2708 WERE LOOSE AND ALLOWING PRODUCT ODOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR. ALSO FOUND WAS A LOOSE LIQUID LINE FLANGE WITH TWO FLANGE BOLT NUTS MISSING AND THE REMAINDER LOOSE.  BOTH THE MANWAY COVER AND THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE WERE REPAIRED BY INSPECTOR MANNAS AND THE CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1545 HOURS, AUGUST 30, 1991.

column168: BEFORE STARTING ON THE TRIP, WE SECURED A VIRGINIA HAULING PERMIT FROM THE VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  UNDER THE PERMIT, WE WERE APPROVED FOR A LOAD HEIGHT OF 15 FEET.  IMMEDIATELY BEFORE LEAVING THE VIRGINIA POWER STATION IN SURRY, VA, WE MEASURED THE LOAD HEIGHT AT 14 FEET 11 INCHES.  AFTER CROSSING THE JAMES RIVER BRIDGE, IN THE PRESENCE OF THE NEWPORT NEWS POLICE, WE AGAIN MEASURED THE LOAD HEIGHT AT 14 FEET II INCHES.  AFTER VERIFYING THAT MEASUREMENT, THE NEWPORT NEWS POLICE ALLOWED US TO PROCEED ALONG OUR ROUTE THROUGH NEWPORT NEWS.  AS OUR TRUCK STARTED DOWN THE ENTRY RAMP (EXIT 61A) TO I-64 WESTBOUND, THE TWO NEWPORT NEWS, VA POLICE ESCORTS STOPPED ALL TRAFFIC IN THE RIGHT LANE FOR OUR APPROACH. THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELLING APPROX. 5-10 MILES PER HOUR.  AS THE DRIVER DROVE THE FRONT RIGHT CORNER OF THE BOX AND CAUSED BOTH THE BOX AND ENCLOSED MOTOR TO BREAK LOOSE FROM THE TRAILER AND FALL TO THE GROUND.  THE REAR ESCORT IMMEDIATELY STOPPED TRAFFIC AND ASKED THE NEWPORT NEWS POLICE TO NOTIFY THEIR HAZMAT TEAM, WHICH THEY PROMPTLY DID.  SOON AFTERWARDS, THE ESCORT CALLED BOTH THE STATE POLICE AND VIRGINIA POWER TO NOTIFY THEN OF THE INCIDENT.  TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE, VIRGINIA POWER CONDUCTED THE SPILL CLEANUP.  THE TRAILER BED (WOOD) WAS CONTAMINATED AND VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION MARK EACH OVERPASS BED.  WE RECOMMEND THAT THE VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION MARK EACH OVERPASS WITH THE HEIGHT CLEARANCE.

column168: COASTAL DRIVER WAS DELIVERING GASOLINE AT A RETAIL FUEL STATION IN DILLON, S.C.  THIS LOCATION DID NOT HAVE A TIGHTFILL CONNECTION FOR THE HOSE AND THEREFORE THE DELIVERY WAS BEING MADE WITH AN UNLOADING SPOUT INTO A 3 INCH UNLOADING PIPE.  THE DRIVER HAD TO GO TO THE RESTROOM IN THE RETAIL STORE AND MADE THE MISTAKE OF LEAVING THE TRUCK WITHOUT CUTTING OFF THE UNLOADING VALVES.  THE GASOLINE BACKED UP INTO THE FILL PIPE AND A SMALL AMOUNT OVERFLOWED ONTO THE STATION DRIVEWAY.  PERSONNEL OF COASTAL TRANSPORT RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY, WENT TO THE SCENE OF THE SPILL AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE SOUTH CAROLINA DEPT. OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL.  APPROX. 10 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE WAS SPILLED AND RAN INTO A STORM DRAIN APROX 40 FEET FROM THE UNLOADING PIPE. THE PRODUCT THAT FLOWED INTO THE DITCH WAS CLEANED UP DOWN STREAM IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH WHICH CONNECTS TO THE STORM SEWER.  THE OFFICIAL OF THE SOUTH CAROLINA DEPT. OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL WAS VERY PLEASED WITH THE CLEAN UP.  THE CUSTOMER THAT OWNS THE RETAIL LOCATION INSTALLED A QUICK COUPLING CONNECTION TO PREVENT THE RECURRENCE OF SUCH AN EVENT.

column168: ON FRIDAY, AUGUST 30, 1991, OUR DRIVER WENT TO THE TIMKEN COMPANY IN WOOSTER, OHIO TO SWITCH THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER THAT TIMKEN FILLS WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID (PICKLING TANK SCALE).  AFTER SITTING THE EMPTY CONTAINER DOWN, HE STARTED TO LOAD THE LOADED CAN ONTO THE CONVERTO UNIT. AFTER THE CAN WAS LOADED, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE CAN WAS STARTING TO LEAK OUT OF THE TAILGATE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON LEAKED OUT UNTIL HE COULD STOP THE LEAKING.  HE TIGHTENED THE TAILGATE SO THAT IT WOULD FORM A TIGHTER SEAL AND HE ALSO MOVED THE MATERIAL TOWARDS THE FRONT OF THE CAN. THE LEAKING WAS TOPPED AND THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY MATERIAL. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL BACK TO THE ENVIRITE FACILITY, APPROXIMATELY 35 MILES.  WE INSTRUCTED HIM TO STOP AND CHECK THE LOAD TO BE SURE THAT THE LEAKING HAD NOT STARTED AGAIN.  HE STOPPED TWICE ON THE RETURN TRIP AND NO ADDITIONAL LEAKING OCCURRED.  HE RETURNED TO THE FACILITY SAFELY.

DRIVER REPORTED THAT THE CHECK VALVE HAD A TENDENCY TO HANG UP FROM TIME TO TIME.  COASTAL TRANSPORT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE AREA WITH THE SPILL KIT ABSORBENT WHICH IS PART OF THE TRUCK'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE EQUIPMENT.  THE CUSTOMER, SALEM LEASING WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CLEAN UP AND THE CHECK VALVE WAS CHANGED THE FOLLOWING DAY TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE TO THIS MISHAP.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPAIRMENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

UPON OPENING TRAILER A WHITE POWDER SUBSTANCE WAS NOTED ON THE OUTSIDE OF SEVERAL PAILS.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED ALONG WITH THE SHIPPER.  SHIPPER AUTHORIZED RETURN OF THE LEAKING PAILS AND DELIVERY OF ALL OTHERS.  ALL DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INSIDE RECOVERY PAILS AND RETURN.

DOCKWORKER PUNCTURED ONE DRUM WITH THE DRUM TRUCK DURING UNLOADING.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO ELIMINATE FURTHER SPILLAGE AND CHEMICAL DRY WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB ALL SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  ALL DEBRIS WAS SWEPT UP AND SEALED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
ONE DRUM WAS CRUSHED IN THE CENTER UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

OPERATOR OF UNIT #1 STATED HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO PULL OUT OF THE LOT AT DOLLAR STRETCHERS.  HE FURTHER STATED HE CHECKED FOR ONCOMING TRAFFIC, BUT THAT HE DIDN'T SEE UNIT #2.  UPON PULLING OUT INTO THE WESTBOUND LANE OF SR22 HE COLLIDED WITH THE TANK TRAILER, SHEARING OFF TWO PIPES IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER.  UNIT #2 WAS WESTBOUND ON SR22 WHEN COLLISION OCCURRED.  MURRYSVILLE V.F.D. WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE TO PUT ABSORBENT ON A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL OIL THAT SPILLED ONTO SR22.

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED THAT SP 67334 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE MANWAY AREA.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR OVERLOADED AND THE LIQUID LEVEL OF THE PRODUCT WAS ABOVE THE OUTAGE GAUGE INSIDE THE TANK.  DUE TO EXPANSION, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY COVER.  PRODUCT LEVEL WAS RESUCED AT THE ROSEVILLE, CALIFORNIA DIESEL RAMP AND THEN THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE DELIVERY INTO TWO (2) TANKS AT THE SAME TIME, A SLIGHT OVER-PRESSURE DEVELOPED IN A THIRD TANK (THE VR VENTS ARE MANIFOLED) AND THE CAP CAME OFF THE THIRD TANK FILL OPENING RELEASING ABOUT 100 GALLONS. PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY JET LINE (CLEANUP CONTRACTOR) ASSISTED BY THE DRIVER AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL).  REPRESENTATIVE FROM RHODE ISLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS ON THE SCENE.
DUST AROUND FRONT CLEAN OUT FITTING ON TRAILER POSSIBLE CRACK IN WELD. ALSO PIN HOLE IN VAPOR RECOVERY.

column168: AS THE DRIVER PULLED UP TO THE TOLL HOSE, HE WAS MADE AWARE OF STEAMING LIQUID COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF HIS VEHICLE.  HE STOPPED TO CHECK THE PROBLEM OUT AND FOUND THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  MAYBE IT WAS PRODUCT THAT WAS LEFT IN THE DOME COVER AREA.  NO CLEAN-UP WAS NECESSARY,

DURING SWITCHING OPERATION, THE SWITCH CREW DISCOVERED ACFX 71850, LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHEN CAR WAS MOVED.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED, WHO RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND REPLACE A BROKEN DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO ITS BILLED DESTINATION.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: ON DATE AND TIME INDICATED ABOVE, STREAKING OF PAINT ACCOUNT OF PRESENCE OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED ON TANK CAR SHELL VICINITY OF DOME, SUSPECTED OF LEAKING.  CAR WAS ISOLATED TO A HOLDING TRACK AT ILLINOIS CENTRAL TRAINYARD.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE TRAINYARD.  SHIPPERS EMPLOYEES INSPECTED LOADING/UNLOADING VALVE AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ACTIVE LEAK; FULLY CLOSED WITH NO EXCEPTIONS TO VALVE OR PLUG.  WITH PLUG REMOVED FROM VALVE (A VERTICAL VALVE), OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY ONE INCH OF PRODUCT ATOP THE CLOSED LIQUID VALVE WHICH WAS REMOVED AND AREA DRIED.  PLUG WAS RE-APPLIED AND TORQUED AND AREA WAS OBSERVED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME.  WITH NO EXCEPTIONS TAKEN TO VALVE AND NO OTHER DEFECTS DETECTED, CAR WAS RELEASED AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HRS SAME DATE AND ALLOWED TO MOVE TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER FURTHER ADVISED AFTER CAR WAS UNLOADED, LOADING/UNLOADING VALVE WAS REMOVED AND TESTED BEYOND OPERATING CAPACITY; IT FAILED AND VALVE WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE.  ALSO, WHEN THIS PRODUCT IS LOADED IT HAS A 20 PSI PAD OF NITROGEN.  SHIPPER WAS CONCLUDED THE POSSIBILITY WITH EVIDENCE THAT PRODUCT QUANTITY WAS INSUFFICIENT TO HIT THE GROUND BUT ENOUGH TO REMOVE PAINT FROM SHELL, FROM VERY SMALL AMOUNT WAS SPILLED IN LOADING PROCESS.

column168: RINCHEM COMPANY INC., RESPONDED TO INCIDENT SAME DATE.  FURNISHED COUNTAINER TO RECOVER LEAKAGE AND TRANSFERRED LOAD FROM TANK CAR TO TANK TRUCKS.  CAR RETUNED TO OWNER FOR REPAIR AFTER MADE EMPTY.

DISCOVERED SMALL LEAK, CONTACTED CHEMTREC WHO IN TURN CONTACTED VULCAN CHEMICALS.  CARRIER TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO CONTAIN SPILLAGE.  VULCAN DISPATCHED RESPONSE TEAM AND TRANSFERRED LADING AND PATCHED LEAK HOLE. LEAK WAS CAUSED BY LINING FAILURE WHICH ALLOWED ACID TO EAT THROUGH OUTER SHELL.

VEHICLE 1 BACKED DOWN AN INCLINE AT CUSTOMER'S FACILITY.  WHILE THE TRAILER WAS ON THE INCLINE, A VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE OPENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT.  WHEN THE DRIVER REALIZED WHAT HAD HAPPENED, HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND MOVED THE TRAILER TO A LEVEL SURFACE.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL C.L. HILL NOTED THAT THE B.S.& B.  100-POUND RUPTURE DISC ON TANK CAR GZTX 11968 WAS PLACED IN THE SAFETY VENT RETAINER UP-SIDE-DOWN.  THE UNDER SIDE OF THE DISC, WHICH WAS IN THE "UP" POSITION, HAD RUPTURED AND THE TOP PORTION OF THE DISC, WHICH WAS ON THE BOTTOM WAS INTACT.  LIQUID WAS ABLE TO SPILL, HOWEVER.  SSA.HM HILL REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC WITH A NEW DISC, PREVENTING ANY LEAKS, AND ALLOWED CAR TO DEPART TO ITS DESTINATION. SSA/HM HILL NOTIFIED CHEMTREC WHO, IN TURN, NOTIFIED SHIPPER KOCH SULFUR IN WICHITA, KS (DICK MAYER) OF THE INCIDENT.

SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED A B.S.& B. 100-POUND DISC HAD RUPTURED; HE PLACED A NEW DISC IN VENT, MADE IT SECURE, HOSED DOWN THE TANK, AND RELEASED IT FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. column42: METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE, IN SOLUTION WITH NOT MORE THAN 9% BY WEIGHT ACTIVE OXYGEN
column168: DOCKMAN DON PAPAJ WAS LOADING A SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLET CONTAINING 48 CARTONS OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE ON TO A TRAILER.  WHILE DOING SO HE INADVERTENTLY JAMMED THIS FREIGHT INTO A SHEET OF PLYWOOD IN THE TRAILER WHICH CAUSED THE TEAR IN THE CARTON AND THE PUNCTURE OF THE BOTTLE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY GREEN ENVIRONMENT.  TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ONE 8 POUND CONTAINER. CARELESSNESS CAUSED THE SPILL.  CORRECTIVE DISCIPLINARY ACTION HAD BEEN TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.  ALSO HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WILL BE COVERED REPEATLY IN PRE SHIFT MEETINGS AND SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: THE YARD CREW (YARD OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR DON ERTLE) AT YERMO NOTIFIED UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAROUS MATERIAL DEAN C. COOPER OF A LEAK FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR ACFX 89255.  SSA/HM COOPER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE 100-POUND RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST; HE REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC, WASHED DOWN THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUE AND RELEASED THE TANK CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  SSA/HM COOPER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT.

DURING A ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTION AT THE CHEYENNE YARDS, UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL D.A. LOW DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 55852.  SSA/HM LOW'S EXAMINATION DETERMINED THE GAUGING ROD SELF-ADJUSTING PACKING GLAND NUT WAS FINGER-TIGHT.  HE SECURED THE PACKING GLAND NUT, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. SSA/HM LOW NOTIFIED CHEMTREC (JIM COOPER) AND SHIPPER COASTAL CHEM (ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER CHARLIE BARNHART) OF THE INCIDENT.

DISTRICT AGENT DON HAMILTON CONTACTED MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE ADVISING THAT MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE D.R. RANKINS HAD RECEIVED COMPLAINTS OF A STRONG PUNGENT ODOR NEAR SERVICE TRACK 209.  THE INVESTIGATION OF MANAGER STINE AND UPRR SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL C.C. SHUPE DETERMINED THE ODOR EMANATED FROM TAMK CAR NATX 77069 AND A SLIGHT LEAKAGE CAME FROM THE NIPPLE THAT ATTACHED THE LIQUID VALVE TO THE LIQUID LINE.  PRESSURE FROM THE HEAT OF THE DAY CAUSED THE LIQUID TO EXPAND AND LEAK FROM THE THREADED JOINT ON THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE AIR INLET VALVE WERE LESS THAN WRENCH-TIGHT; THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE, HOWEVER, OF LEAKAGE AT EITHER LOCATION.  STINE AND SHUPE TIGHTENED THE PLUGS.  CHEMTREC (SUSAN TRACY), TRAIN MANAGEMENT, AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE DAVE SMIDT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  SHIPPER INDICATED CONSIGNEE WOULD MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.

column168: AT APROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, AUGUST 20, 1991, A SWITCHMAN REPORTED TO ATM J.B. NORWOOD THAT TANK CAR PSPX 591 WAS LEAKING AT TOP OF TANK. ATM J.B. NORWOOD REPORTED THE TANK LEAKING TO GENERAL EQUIPMENT FOREMAN L.M. BLOCK, WHO DISCOVERED THE TANK LEAKING AT PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE DUE TO BEING OVERLOADED AND HEAT OF DAY CAUSING EXPANSION OF THE LIQUID. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO TRACK 170, THE ISOLATION TRACK, AND A CONTAINER WAS PLACED TO CATCH RUN OFF, WHICH EVAPORATED QUICKLY. THE SUPERVISOR OF TRAIN OPERATIONS AT EULESS WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS. THE SHIPPER, PHILLIPS PETROLEUM COMPANY OUT OF ELKHART, TEXAS, ARRIVED AT 0100 HOURS AUGUST 21, 1991, BUT WAS UNABLE TO REDUCE THE LOAD DUE TO LACK OF PROPER TOOLS.  DUE TO TEMPERATURE DROP, THE TANK CAR STOPPED LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 1945 HOURS.  THEY DECIDED TO WAIT FOR THE PROPER EQUIPMENT WHICH ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, AUGUST 22, AND CAR LOAD REDUCED AND OKAY AT 1430 HOURS AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THEIR PLANT.  PSPX 591 WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVE TO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THIS IS A MATTER OF INFORMATION, LAST NIGHT AT APPROX. 11PM JOB 250 FOUND A LEAKING TANK (GAPX 10014) IN YARD 11-59. GAPX 10014 WAS APPARENTLY OVERFILL/LOADED WITH LPG (PROPANE) AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD VENTED AND TRIED TO SEAT BACK INTO PLACE, CUTTING THE GASKET WHICH KEPT THE VALVE VENTING CONSTANTLY. TRAINMASTER O.O.ROBUCK, THE FIRST OFFICER AT THE SCENE, MADE A VISIBLE INSPECTION AND MADE THE DETERMINATION TO CALL THR HAZ. MAT. TEAM.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, THR ENTIRE NORTH YARD WAS EVACUATED TO THE SOUTH END OF THE PARK AND THE HAZ. MAT TEAM HAD SET UP COMMAND POST IN THE MIDDLE OF THE YARD. AFTER CONSULTING WITH EVERYONE AT THE SCENE, MYSELF AND TWO FIREMEN MADE INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR VALVES AND FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE VENTING WHICH NO FIELD REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  BY THIS TIME WE HAD PLACED A CALL TO GEORGIA GULF AND TWO REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AND CONCURRED WITH US THAT NO FIELD REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. AT THIS TIME WE HAD TWO ALTERNATIVES, TO TRANSFER THE ENTIRE PRODUCT INTO TANK TRUCKS PROVIDING THEY COULD FIND THE TANK TRUCKS AND THE TIME CONSUMPTION OF APPROX. 10 TO 15 HRS IN TRANSFERRING THE PRODUCT.  THE OTHER ALTERNATIVE WAS TO SPECIAL THE TANK CAR TO GEORGIA GULF. AFTER A BRIEF DISCUSSION WITH EVERYONE IN CONCERN IT WAS IN AGREEMENT THE BEST SOLUTION TO OUR PROBLEM WAS TO SPECIAL THE TANK CAR TO GEORGIA GULF, SINCE THE TANK CAR HAD COOLED DOWN TREMENDOUSLY AND WAS VENTING SLOWLY. WITH THE PROPER AFFORDED PROTECTION THE TANK CAR COULD MOVED SAFELY TO ITS DESTINATION. WITH THE TEAM OF OFFICERS MADE OF TRAINMANSTER O.O.ROBUCK, C. REEVES AND MYSELF, WE DEPARTED THE NORTH YARD WITH THE SPECIAL CONSISTING OF ENGINE 33, 6 COVER CARS ON EACH END OF THE LEAKER AND SPOTTED THE CAR AT GEORGIA GULF AT APPROX. 4:30 A.M.

AT 1025 A.M., DOCKMAN, PHIL MONTES, WAS HANDLING THE ABOVE SHIPMENT.  IT WAS COMBINED ON A SKID WITH OTHER SHIPMENTS.  AS HE TURNED TO APPROACH 90 DOOR, THE CARTON FELL OFF THE SKID AND 2 GLASS JUGS INSIDE CRACKED.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY COVERED WITH FIBREBOARD AND OIL DRY.  THERE WAS MINIMAL EXPOSURE TO FUMES.  HERITAGE REMEDIATION WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS.  CHEMTREK AND VWR HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.

THE SWITCH CREW NOTIFIED UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL G.B. REEDER THAT A CLEAR LIQUID WAS LEAKING FEOM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR GATX 18618.  SSA/HM REEDER CONTACTED SHIPPER KKB OIL COMPANY (BILL BOWEN) TO VERIFY THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE BILL BOWEN REPORTED THE CAR HAD BEEN LOADED WITH HEATED CRUDE OIL AND HAD SAT.  THE OIL HAD SINCE SOLIDIFIED AND THE WATER HAD SEPARATED FROM THE OIL.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE BOWEN'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS NOT TIGHT AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED TIGHT.  HE MADE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR SHIPMENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: PASSENGER SORENSEN CONCEALED AN ACID FILLED BATTERY INSIDE A SUITCASE AND PRESENTED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION ON FLIGHT 1265 AUGUST 23.  THE ACID SPILL CAUSED DAMAGED TO HIS SUITCASE AND TWO OTHER SUITCASES.  TWO EMPLOYEES (BAGGAGE HANDLERS) COMPLAINED OF BURNS - THEY WERE OBSERVED BY MEDICAL AND RELEASED.

WHILE DOCK FOREMAN, JEFF VIRLEE, WAS WALKING HIS ZONE, HE NOTICED LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THE TOP OF ONE DRUM OF 30 LOT LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHERE OTHER FREIGHT WAS LOADED AND PUCNTURED THE TOP OF THE DRUM.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: THE TRANSPORTATION DRIVER - MR.  KEN HAGGARD - WAS THROUGH UNLOADING AND WAS UNHOOKING HIS HOSES.  THE END OF THE HOSE COUGHT KEN'S CHEMICAL SUIT PANT LEG (LEFT) AND PUSHED IT INSIDE HIS CHEMICAL BOOTS.  SOME RESIDUE LEFT IN THE HOSE RAN INTO HIS LEFT BOOT CAUSING BURNS TO HIS LEFT ANKLE AND FOOT.  KEN RECEIIVED FIRST AID ON THE SCENE AND WENT TO THE MED CLINIC IN IDAHO FALLS.  THE DOCTOR WHO LOOKED AT IT SAID IT WAS  A MINOR BURN AND THAT IT WOULD HEAL WITHOUT ANY PROBLEM.  10 DAYS LATER (08/23/91) KEN GOT A SECOND DOCTOR IN SALT LAKE CITY TO LOOK AT THE INJURY AND THEY DECIDED TO GRAFT SOME SKIN TO A SMALL AREA OF KEN'S ANKLE TO FACILITATE QUICKER HEALING.  SUBSEQUENTLY, KEN WAS HOSPITALIZED ON THE 26TH OF AUGUST, 1991 TO GET THE SKIN GRAFTING DONE.  AN IMMEDIATE INCIDENT REPORT WAS NOT MADE AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT BECAUSE THE REQUIREMENT OF HOSPITALIZATION WAS NOT EVIDENT AT THAT TIME.

column168: ON 8/17/91 (0815 HOURS), ASSISTANT TERMINAL MANAGER UPRR (D. BIRD) NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) S.D. WHITED THAT BULK TANK SCXU 871877 CONTAINING A HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS LEAKING AT THEIR FACILITY.  ALSO ADVISED THAT THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND OIL DRY WAS BEING USED TO CONTAIN LEAKING PRODUCT. SA/HM WHITED RESPONDED AND MADE A CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT ALL VALVES WERE IN THE CLOSED POSITION WITH THE CAP IN PLACE AND SEALED.  THERE WAS NO LEAK NOTED AT THIS TIME AND THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED WAS BEING CONTAINED.  MATERIAL WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED IN OVER PACK DRUMS.  AREA WAS SWEPT AND FIVE GALLONS OF EMULSIFYING AGENT WAS USED TO COVER THE AREA. SUBSEQUENT CONVERSATION WITH MECAHNIC GARY MCDANIEL DETERMINED THAT HE HAD NOTED LEAK AND WAS ABLE TO MOVE THE DISCHARGE VALVE HANDLE (1/8 INCH) WHICH SECURED LEAK.  REINSPECTION OF THE DISCHARGE VALVE HANDLE DETERMINED A SMALL LOCKING PIN ON VALVE HANDLE HAD THE BOTTOM END BEVELED AND WAS NOT COMPLETELY IN THE LOCKING SLOT ON VALVE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1210 HOURS, FRIDAY 6, 1991. DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR CONLEY OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-17180 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.) WHILE CONDUCTING INSPECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AT THE CONRAIL, COLUMBUS, OHIO.  CAR WAS IOSLATED AND CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  INSPECTOR CONLEY DETERMINED THAT LEAK WAS FROM THE CAR'S SAFETY VALVE.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE SHIPPER (LUBRIZOL) ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1940 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 7, 1991 AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE SAFETY VALVE.  TANK CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 7, 1991.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, FRIDAY, AUGUST 30, 1991, EMPLOYEES ON CONRAIL TRAIN OIPI-9 SMELLED CHEMICAL ODOR COMING FROM TANK CARS RAIX-2715 AND RAIX-2708 IN THE TRAIN,  CARS WERE ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES  WERE NOTIFIED.  CRESSON, PA FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED. AFTER THE CARS WERE EXMAMINED BY THE CRESSON FIRE DEPARTMENT THEY WERE SET OUT OF THE TRAIN TO TRACK #5 WEST AT THE CONRAIL CRESSEON PA RAIL YARD.  SENOIR INSPECTOR T MANNAS OF THE AAR.BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CARS AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, AUGUST 30, AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS OF TANK CAR RAIX-2715 WERE LOOSE AND ALLOWING PRODUCT ODOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR. ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1545 HOURS, AUGUST 30, 1991.

FLUID SURROUNDING A WHEELCHAIR IN THE BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS DISCOVERED UPON UNLOADING.  THE WHEELCHAIR AND BATTERIES WERE REMOVED AND CLEANED. THE AIRCRAFT (9015) WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND IN-DEPTH INSPECTION AND CLEAN-UP PERFORMED.

UPON OPENING THE CARGO DOOR OF THE 737 AIRCRAFT, THE RAMP AGENT NOTICED THE SMELL OF GAS.  THE SOURCE OF THE SMELL WAS IDENTIFIED AS COMING FROM A BACK PACK.  THE FAA WAS IMMEDIATELY ADVISED AND CAME DIRECTLY TO THE AIRPORT AND INTERVIEWED THE PASSENGER. THE PASSENGER BOARDED FLIGHT 61 IN CORDOVA, AK BOUND FOR ANCHORAGE, AK. HE ARRIVED AT THE LAST MINUTE FOR HIS FLIGHT AND DID NOT REMEMBER THAT HE HAD A SMALL BUTANE CAMP STOVE INSIDE.  PASSENGER WAS PRETTY HUMBLE.  FAA SAID THEY WOULD BE CONTACTING THE PASSENGER AT A LATER DATE TO CONTINUE INVESTIGATION.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS REACHING DOWN TO PICK UP RADIO MICROPHONE, VEERED OFF ONTO SHOULDER OF ROAD AND LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED CAUSING THE TANK TO BREAK LOOSE OF THE CHASSIS, AND SIMULTANEOUSLY THE PUMP BROKE LOOSE FROM THE TANK, CAUSING THE TANK TO LEAK.  THE ELECTRICAL CABLE IN THE REAR SPARKED AGAINST THE FRAME CAUSING THE TANK TO IGNITE.  OUR DRIVER RECEIVED 2ND & 3RD DEGREE BURNS ON HIS UPPER TORSO, ARMS AND FACE, AND CUTS TO THE BACK OF HIS HEAD AND BACK OF HIS RIGHT LEG.  HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO ST. LUKE'S BURN TRAUMA UNIT.  HE WAS RELEASED 9/13/91. CHEMTREC, THE COUNTY SHERIFF, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND IOWA DNR WERE NOTIFIED.  A TELEPHONE REPORT (#85256) WAS CALLED IN TO THE U.S. COAST GUARD (PETTY OFFICER EVANSON) AT 1650, 8/23/91. THE HIGHWAY WAS BLOCKED WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS ALLOWED TO BURN AND WAS REOPENED THE EVENING OF 8/23/91.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 AM, INDUCTION RECEIVED CONTAINER #3324 ON THE PASSENGER SIDE.  SHORTLY AFTER THE CONTAINER WS BEING UNLOADED, AN UNKNOWN LIQUID IN THE CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED.  I THEN NOTIFIED MARK BOHANNON OF A POSSIBLE HAZARDOUS SPILL IN INDUCTION.  PHILL CALLED MAINTENANCE AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOCK THE HAZMAT LOCKER. THE SPILL WAS THEN CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINER AND ISOLATED OUTSIDE OF THE MAINTENANCE BUILDING.  MAINTENANCE, ALSO, ISOLATED THE ACTUAL SUBSTANCE AND THE DRYING AGENT IN A CIRCUS CART OUTSIDE OF THE MAINTENANCE BUILDING. ROBERT A MIZE

AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 AM ON 8/22/91 I WAS INFORMED BY MAINTENANCE (GARY CARTER) THAT THERE WAS A HAZMAT SPILL BY THE HAZMAT CART BY INDUCTION. OBSERVING THE SPILL, I NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A BOX THAT HAD BROKE OPEN INSIDE A POSTAL BAG.  THIS BOX WAS LEAKING LIQUID AND GIVING OFF HARMFUL VAPORS.  AT THIS POINT I CLEARED THE AREA OF ALL PERSONNEL AND CONTACTED MARK BOHANNON TO DETERMINE WHAT THE MATERIAL WAS AND TO DETERMINE THE HARMFUL EFFECTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE MATERIAL. PAT PLASTERS OF THE POSTAL SERVICE HAD OPENED THE BOX AND CHECKED THE CONTENTS AND DETERMINED THAT THIS PRODUCT SHOULD NOT BE IN OUR SYSTEM. DRUM WAS PLACED IN BAGGAGE CART 875-12.

THIS RELEASE LASTED FOR ABOUT TWENTY MINUTES UNTIL THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED MAINTENANCE YARD OPERATIONS (RICK PENNINGTON) THAT A SAFETY VALVE HAD A VALVE HANDLE THAT WOULD SHUT OFF RELEASE, WHICH WAS DONE. AT 0430 HRS, 08/24/91. THE ABOVE CAR AGAIN RELEASED VAPORS INTO THE AIR. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) C.L. HILL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE CAR HAD BUILT UP A PRESSURE AND WAS RELEASING THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH TWO SAFETY VALVES).  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED SAME DATE, REDUCED THE PRESSURE AND CAR WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DEAN L. WHITELEY NOTED SMALL ACCUMULATION OF DRIED PRODUCT AROUND THE BASE OF VACUUM RELIEF VALVE ON TANK CAR UTLX 85149.  SSA/HM WHITELEY OBSERVED TANKCAR BEING  SWITCHED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED FRESH PRODUCT ON THE TOP OUTSIDE PORTION OF VALVE. VALVE WAS REPLACED WITH A PIPE PLUG TO PREVENT FURTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT. CHEMTREC AND OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL (SAM MORRIS) TACOMA, WA. WERE NOTIFIED.

ON AUGUST 26, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 A.M., WHILE MOVING TANKCARS, TANK CAR LOADER, H. BARNETT, REPORTED A LEAK ON TANK CAR A-71530.  R-22 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE ASSEMBLY. LYNN FERGUSON, RHONDA LANE AND I WENT TO INVESTIGATE.  H. BARNETT REPORTED THAT THE LEAK WAS SMALL AT FIRST, BUT THEN BLEW OUT SOME GASKET MATERIAL, WHEREUPON LIQUID BEGAN POURING OUT. SINCE WE HAD AN EMPTY R-22 TANK CAR ON SITE, WE QUICKLY MOVED A-71530 ONTO THE STORAGE TRACK AND BEGAN TRANSFERRING FROM THE LEAKING CAR THROUGH BOTH LIQUID LINES ON TOP AND CONTINUED TRANSFERRING UNTIL VAPOR SHOWED THROUGH THE SIGHT GLASS.  THE LEAKING CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO THE LAODING DOCK AND UNLOADED THROUGH THE BOTTOM VALVE INTO A TANK TRUCK.  ALL LIQUID WAS REMOVED FROM A-71530 BY 5:50 P.M.  THE REMAINING VAPOR WAS THEN PULLED BACK TO THE RECOVERY SYSTEM.  WE ESTIMATE THAT WE RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 116,310 POUNDS OF R-22, INDICATING A LOSS OF 42,240 POUNDS OF PRODUCT. WE FEEL THAT THERE ARE SEVERAL CORRECTIVE ACTIONS THAT COULD BE TAKEN TO KEEP THIS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.  THE BEST WAY TO AVOID THE RECURRENCE OF THIS PROBLEM WOULD BE TO REMOVE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FROM ALL OUR TANK CARS.  IF THIS IS NOT POSSIBLE, WE SUGGEST THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: 1. MAKE SURE THAT THE CAR SHOP TORQUES FLANGES PROPERLY 2. HAVE EACH CAR SHOP INSPECT AT LEAST ONE TANK CAR UNDER OUR SUPERVISION TO INSURE THEIR UNDERSTANDING OF OUR NEEDS AND EXPECTATIONS 3. WHEN LEAVING THE SHOP, TANK CARS SHOULD BE CLEANED AND PURGED WITH NITROGEN 4. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE SHOULD BE REBUILT AFTER EACH TRIP 5. ALL VALVE SEATS AND GASKETS MUST BE MECHANICALLY AND CHEMICALLY COMPATIBLE WITH WHATEVER PRODUCT THAT TANK CAR IS TO BE USED FOR

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE SWITCH CREW AT ALEXANDRIA, LA AND OBSERVED LIQUID SPURTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR TILX 100242 DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED.  SSA/HM ROBINSON'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED FROM A FAILED RUPTURE DISC (BS&B, 100 PSI) IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  ROBINSON OBSERVED THAT THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY COVER CAP WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION AT THE TIME OF HIS INSPECTION.  SSA/HM ROBINSON INSTALLED A NEW RUPTURE DISC (BS&B, 100 PSI) AND SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC, MR.  BOB NELSON AND MR. TIM BOLTON OF PHELPS DODGE, AND THE LOUSIANA STATE POLICE WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.
PASSENGER DID NOT DECLARE HAZ-MAT BEFORE SHIPPING AS CHECKED BAGGAGE. HAZ-MAT WAS DISCOVERED DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  JOHN WHITE, SPECIAL AGENT IN ANCHORAGE WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED BY DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT (DSA) TOM GRIFFITH ADVISING THAT GATX 10736 WAS LEAKING.  SSA/HM HUGGINS RESPONDED AND DSA GRIFFITH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CLIMAX CHEMICAL OF ARDEN, NV.  DSA GRIFFITH SPOKE WITH MR. CHESTER KNOX, SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE AND MR. KNOX RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. INSPECTION DETERMINED THE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR, NEAR THE CENTER ALONG A SEAM IN THE OUTER JACKET.  THE EXACT POINT OF LEAK COULD NOT BE LOCATED, THE LEAK WAS IN THE INTERIOR LINER AND PROTECTED BY THE EXTERIOR JACKET, MR. KNOX PLUGGED THE LEAK WITH HEMP ROPE AND NEUTRALIZED SPILLED ACID WITH SODA ASH. THE CAR WAS BAD ORDERED FOR REPAIR AND MOVED TO CLIMAX CHEMICAL TO BE CLEANED OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT AND THEN REPAIRED.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRAIN MANAGEMENT ADVISED THAT TANK CAR ARIX 1152 WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP.  CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED AND SHIPPER HAD BEEN NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS VENTING AND IT WAS ENCASED IN ICE.  NO OTHER FITTINGS WERE VENTING.  AIRCO REPRESENTATIVE, CLIFF ELLIOTT, 1-800-345-9052.  MR. ELLIOTT ADVISED THAT REPAIRMEN, RICKY TEAGUE WOULD RESPOND AND DETERMINE WHAT PARTS WOULD BE NEEDED. MR. TEAGUE DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY VALVES WOULD HAVE TO BE REPLACED. PRODUCT TURNED TO A SOLID AND UPON SAFETY VALVE REPLACEDMENT PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO REVERT THE PRODUCT BACK TO A LIQUID.  THE TANK CAR WOULD NOT MAINTAIN ADEQUATE PRESSURE AND WAS OFFLOADED INTO AIRCO TRUCKS.  ARIX 1152 WAS THEN SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

ON FRIDAY, 8/17/91, NIGHT OPERATIONS AT 0259, HAZ-MAT DISPATCH WAS CONTACTED VIA RADIO BY SORT SUPERVISOR, DORIS CROTHERS (GROUND 06).  SHE REPORTED A SPILL, ENTER THROUGH DOOR C-8.  THIS SPILL WAS CALLED IN AS A LEAKING SHIPMENT, NO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, NO ODOR.  CERT. 06 (DON FLOREA, PART-TIME HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST) AND CERT 12 (RHONDA CLONCH, PART-TIME HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST) RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT 0329.  UPON ARRIVAL, WE DID NOT DETECT AND ODOR.  AS WE OPENED THE SHIPMENT, (A FIBREBOARD BOX) WE DETECTED A STRONG ALCOHOL TYPE ODOR.  WE QUICKLY CLOSED THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND MOVED OUTSIDE THE SORT CENTER TO INVESTIGATE.  WE THEN DONNED OUR CARTRIDGE MASKS AND REOPENED THE SHIPMENT AND REMOVED THE CONTENTS.  THE INNER CONTAINERS THAT WERE LEAKING WERE PLASTIC 2 OZ. SCREW-TYPE.  THEY WERE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE MARKED FLAMMABLE LIQUID, AND HAD NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  THE CONTAINER LABEL READS AS FOLLOWS: "FLAMMABLE-KEEP FROM HEAT-IRRITANT, EYES, SKIN & RESPIRATORY, KEEP CONTAINER CLOSED" (MIL-F-14256 LA) USE EYE/SKIN PROTECTION, SEE MSDS.  OUTER CONTAINER: SINGLE WALL FIBREBOARD BOX, SECURED WITH PACKAGING TAPE.  MARKING AS FOLLOWS: TOP: AIRWAYBILL AND LABEL (SEE ATTACHED INFO) FORNT: NO MARKINGS LEFT SIDE: NO MARKINGS BACK: NO MARKINGS RIGHT SIDE: NO MARKINGS, BUT SHOWED STAINS FROM LEAKAGE BOTTOM: MANUFACTURER SEAL INFO; THACKER CONTAINER CO., DALLAS, TEXAS. COMPLIES WITH SPEC. PPP-B-636-J, WITH MRA.  SIZE 18X12X12.  OTHER PREPRINTED INFO INCLUDES THE SEAL AND LETTERING "RECYCLE". INNER CONTAINER: 2 - CLEAR PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH METAL PULL RODS TO OPEN AND CLOSE, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE EACH IN A PLASTIC BAG AND THE CLOSURE STAPLED.  THE BOTTOM WAS STAMPED "MONSANTO". 1 - CLEAR PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH THE LABEL "XURON CORP" NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  THIS CONTAINER WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG (ROSIN FLUX) AND THE CLOSURE STAPLED. 1 - BROWN GLASS CONTAINER WITH SCREW TOP CLOSURE, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  THIS CONTAINER WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG WITH THE CLOSURE STAPLED.  THIS CONTAINER WAS LABELED "FORMULA 1547" "KESTER, LIQUID FLUX" NO PH READING. ALL FOUR OF THE INNER CONTAINERS, WHICH WERE IN PLASTIC BAGS, LEAKED RESULTING IN THE SPILL AND ODOR.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT IN THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS BUBBLE WRAP AROUND ALL OF THE INSTRUMENTS AND INNER CONTAINERS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND HAD NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFIECATION. THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED, BAGGED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM IN ILN HAZ-MAT PERSONNEL AND IS BEING HELD IN THE ILN HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. *MATERIALS THAT WERE NON-HAZ AND NOT AFFECTED BY THE LEAKING PRODUCT HAVE BEEN MOVED TO DESTINATION.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON AND SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) DEAN WOMACK WERE NOTIFIED OF A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 99383.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SA/HM WOMACK RESPONDED. SA/HM WOMACK'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE LEAK TO BE A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE COMING FROM A DEFECTIVE THERMOMETER WELL ON UTLX 99383. ON 08/21/91, JAMES MALKOWSKY WAS WORKING AS A CONDUCTOR ON THE LHH86/21 AT COADY YARD ON THE BAYTOWN SUBDIVISION.  WHILE THE TRAIN WAS SWITCHING CARS MALKOWSKY INHALED VAPORS COMING FROM GATX 47112, CONTAINING SPENT SULFURIC ACID.  MALKOSKY WAS TAKEN TO GULF COAST HOSPITAL, TREATED BY DR. MANAMUS AND RELEASED. CHARLES NELSON, MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, PHIL ALLEN, MANAGER RHONE POULENC AND DENNIS ST. JOHN, MANAGER LYONDELL PETROCHEMICAL INSPECTED THE CAR. ABOUT 2:30 A.M. DOCKMAN STRIPPING TRAILER 5893 SMELLED FUMES IN TRAILER AND BECAME GUEAZY.  THE FORMAN SPOTTED A 5 GALLON PAIL OF POISON B AND WARNED EVERYBODY AWAY FROM THE TRAILER AND PULLED IT AWAY FROM THE DOCK TO AN ISOLATED AREA.  I RECEIVED A CALL AT 2:$0 AM AND TOLD HIM TO SEND DOCKMAN JIM SMITH TO THE HOSPITAL.  JIM REFUSED TO GO.  I CALLED MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL, A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR AND THEN I LEFT FOR THE TERMINAL ARRIVING AT 4:30 A.M.  I CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER IN CANADA. 613-996-6666 TOLD HIM WHAT I HAD AND REQUESTED AN MSDS SHEET FAXED TO ME. I RECEIVED THAT, AND MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL SHOWED UP AT 5:00 P.M., PLACED PAIL IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER WHICH HAD A SMALL WER SPOT.  I INTERVIEWED JIM SMITH AND HE CLAIMED HE WAS FINE AND DID NOT WANT TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: HOLMAN TRANSFER WAREHOUSE FORCES WERE PREPARING MP 253956 FOR UNLOADING AND NOTED STEEL DRUMS STACKED TWO HIGH HAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORTATION RESULTING IN LIDS OF 15 STEEL DRUMS COMING OPEN. SOME PRODUCT HAD ABSORBED MOISTURE IN THE AIR CREATING SOME LIQUID MATERIAL THAT RAN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE DRUMS. ALL CONTAMINATED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. PORTLAND OFFICE POLICE/HAZMAT DEPT WAS NOT NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. ACCOUNTS SUPV LESLIE LACROSS, HOLMAN TRANSFER, PORTLAND, WAS CONTACTED FOR RECORSE COVERING BOXCAR.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER, MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, DAVID MYERS NOTED TANK CAR GATX 18469 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA.  ASARCO REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE STAINLESS STEEL FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  REPRESENTATIVE REPLACED THE DISC AND CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.

PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING OUT OF SAFETY VALVE AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF CAR.  C. SHUPE WITH UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD COMPANY WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE AND HE CALLED CHEMICAL TRECH AND TALKED WITH SHIPPER.  METRO EAST INDUSTRIES, INC. WERE NOTIFIED TO TEST SAFETY VALVE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 5:50 P.M., AUGUST 12, 1991, A REPLACEMENT SAFETY VALVE WAS DELIVERED TO THE ALTON AND SOUTHERN AND WAS INSTALLED ON CAR.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: SWITCH CREW AT LONGVIEW, TX NOTICED RCRX 1170 HAD LIQUID ON THE SIDES AND TOPS OF THE CAR.  THE LIQUID APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM A FITTING ON THE TOP OF THE CAR. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO REPAIR THE CAR.  SHIPPER RESPONDED AND REPAIRED CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

ON FRIDAY 8/17/91, NIGHT OPERATIONS AT 0259, HAZ MAT DISPATCH WAS CONTACTED VIA RADIO BY SORT SUPERVISOR, DORIS CROTHERS (GROUND 06), SHE REPORTED A SPILL, ENTER THROUGH DOOR C-8.  THE SPILL WAS CALLED IN AS A LEAKING SH IPMENT, NO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, NO ODOR.  CERT 06 (DON FLOREA, PART-TIME HAZ MAT SPECIALIST) AND CERT 12 (RHONDA CLONCH, PART TIME HAZ MAT SPECIALIST) RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT 0329.  UPON ARRIVAL, WE DID NOT DETECT AN ODOR.  AS WE OPENED THE SHIPMENT, (A FIBERBOARD BOX) WE DETECTED A STRONG ALCOHOL TYPE ODOR.  WE QUICKLY CLOSED THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND MOVED OUTSIDE THE SORT CENTER TO INVESTIGATE.  WE THEN DONNED OUR CARTRIDGE MASKS AND REOPENED THE SHIPMENT AND REMOVED THE CONTENTS.  THE INNER CONTAINER THAT WERE LEAKING WERE PLASTIC 2 OZ. SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE TYPE.  THERE WERE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE MARKED FLAMMABLE LIQUID, AND HAD NO POSITIVE "FLAMMABLE-KEPP FROM HEAT-IRRITANT, EYES, SKIN AND RESPIRATORY, KEEP CONTAINER CLOSED" (MIL-F-14256 LA) USE EYE/SKIN PROTECTION, SEE MSDS. OUTER CONTAINER: SINGLE WALL FIBERBOARD, BOX SECURED WITH PACKAGING TAPE. MARKING AS FOLLOWS: TOP: AIRWAY BILL AND LABEL (SEE ATTACHED INFO). FRONT: NO MARKINGS LEFT SIDE: NO MARKING BACK: NO MARKINGS RIGHT SIDE; NO MARKINGS, BUT SHOWED STAINS FROM LEAKAGE. BOTTOM: MANUFACTURER SEAL INFO; THACKER CONTAINER CO, DALLAS, TEXAS. COMPLIES WITH SPEC. PPP-B-636-J, WITH MRA.  SIZE 18X12X12. OTHER PREPRINTED INFO INCLUDES THE SEAL AND LETTERING "RECYCLE" INNER CONTAINER: 2 - CLEAR PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH METAL PULL RODS TO OPEN AND CLOSE, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE EACH IN A PLASTIC BAG AND THE CLOSURE STAPED.  THE BOTTOM WAS STAMPED "MONSANTO". 1 - BORWN GLASS CONTAINER WITH SCREW TOP CLOSURE, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  THIS CONTAINER WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG WITH THE CLOSURE STAPED.  THIS CONTAINER WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG WITH THE CLOSURE STAPLED. THIS CONTAINER WAS LABELED "FORMULA 1547" "kESTER, LIQUID  FLUX" NO PH READINGS. ALL FOUR OF THE INNER CONTAINER, WHICH WERE IN PLASTIC BAGS, LEAKED RESULTING IN THE SPILL AND ODOR.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS BUBBLE WRAP AROUND OFF OF THE INSTRUMENTS AND INNER CONTAINERS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND HAD NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATION. THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED, BAGGED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM BY ILN HAZ-MAT PERSONNEL AND IS BEING HELD IN THE ILN HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. *MATERIALS THAT WERE NON-HAZ AND NOT AFFECTED BY THE LEAKIN PRODUCT HAE BEEN MOVED TO DESTINATION.
